segments.text: commodity group is the most skillful and which is perhaps the least skillful in maximizing their capability?
Well, you know, I'm not really sure, but I'm guessing the cattlemen are probably as powerful as anybody in terms of getting pressure put on them.
But then again, the cattlemen
There's not that many government programs in cattle, but as far as if you want to muster some power, I would think the Cattlemen's Association would be.
All right, but in marketing their product, are they skillful?
Skillful.
In getting about as well, doing about as well as the price could be?
That's, I couldn't, you know, I can't separate out a group that's that skillful in marketing their product.
Cooperatives, probably the dairy guys,
might be because of just the nature of their product and the nature of their organization.
The dairy people might be the better marketers.
But didn't you tell me, wasn't it you or somebody else told me that the Vidalia onion people that have done much more skillfully the marketing of their onion than the Texans have of the 1015s.
I'm not sure I told you that, but I presume Vidalia is maybe better known.
That's what it's meaning.
Yeah, it may have done a better.
And that our crop, our product is probably as good or better.
Yeah, the guys in the valley, bless their hearts, have not been, well, they're so independent.
They're so individualistic that it's hard to get them to work together.
And that's part of what we were doing down there in the early 60s was trying to get them,
Marketing orders were looked at as almost communistic.
We don't want that.
That's bad.
That's communist.
Almost.
They were going to add the paper like that.
So they haven't been, whereas California is just the opposite.
California is known for marketing orders and cooperatives and Sunkist and Calcott and all that kind of thing.
They've done, if you want to see how to market stuff historically, you went to California.
The Texans were...
You know, we don't want that stuff.
We'll do it our way and suffered for it, I think.
California, you know, Florida is not a good example of good marketing and the money they put into it.
They put up the money to do it, orange juice and grapefruit and things like that.
So as far as skillfully marketing their stuff, I don't know that, you know, somebody's probably shooting me but I'm trying to think of a group that I think is really good at that in Texas.
It may be some of the grapefruit guys have their own associations.
What about among those that have been least successful?
Well, you know, you've got one side of the coin, there's the other.
Marketing is where a lot of them have producers produce.
That's what they want to do.
They want to produce.
And they assume that having produced, they're owed a fair price.
And when they don't get it, they don't understand it.
They don't want to put the time and effort into marketing or risk management.
It's a tough education process because producing this stuff does take a lot of time and effort.
And they just don't, many of them want to get into the marketing side of it.
I think probably Plains Cotton Cooperative out in Lubbock has done some good work marketing their stuff, marketing their cotton.
And I think you could probably go to maybe the Texas Grapefruit or Citrus Association in the Valley.
They've done some good work.
But agriculture by its nature, even though it's had government programs all these many years, is a bunch of damned independent people.
They're hard to get to work together.
In all of your marketing research, which was the most enjoyable, most pleasant, most fun?
Well...
I think working with the pecan people, their laid-back bunch, has been, was interesting.
The honey people are, and I'm mostly, when I say marketing, I'm really more in the price analysis part of it, but the honey people are fun to work with.
What little I've done with them just the last few years.
But I can't really think of any that weren't interesting to try to figure out how they do this and why this happens and try to forecast the price.
They've all, you know, it's a bunch of cases.
And I can't think of the ones that scare me the most were in the valley where these guys didn't want you messing in their business.
Of which, of all of those tasks, all your work, of which are you most proud?

Well, trying to explain price behavior in something like pecans or a little bit in the honey thing and the citrus crops in the valley where you try to look at the market, see what's happening, imports, exports, stocks, whatever, and try to forecast the prices and see if you can actually explain why the price did what it did.
Do you remember any specific examples of where suddenly a light came on and somebody jumped on board and agreed with you?
Oh, yeah.
I think that happens to some extent in pecans and some of the citrus work we did in the valley.
And that's always reassuring that you see them understand what's happening, why this is happening to us.
That's rewarding.
Like when you see it in class, you know, when kids understand something that you're trying to teach, it's the same thing with adults.
And they appreciate it because basically this whole economic side thing, like the beekeepers just don't,
grasp what's going on.
Does anybody ever write a note or pick up the phone or anything to say, hey, I really appreciate your work?
Once in a while you get that.
Once in a while.
I think some get it more than others.
But I have gotten letters, yeah, of appreciation for talks here and there or a publication.
When they request your publications, you kind of get the feeling that they do appreciate what you're doing.
Of all your publications, of which are you most proud?
I suppose it could be some actually in trade publications, because I know they've been read by more people than a journal article.
I suppose in terms of just selfish pride, the ones you've had in refereed journals are the ones that you think are the most prestigious.

But when I get something in American Beekeeper or Pecan South or some trade publication, I feel as good about it because I know more people have read it and probably gotten more out of it than they did out of a journal article.
But if somebody walked up to you today and said, give me two or three of your best, what would you have?
I'd probably pick up the journal articles because they are refereed.
Journal of Futures Market, there's a couple in there.
A couple about what?
about the futures market, risk management, futures and options contracts.
I didn't really have that many, let's see, southern, most of my, I had one or two in agricultural, the mother journal.
Most of my stuff was in regional journals or what did I just say, the future journal of futures markets.
So I would probably pick those out and say this is, you know, grade D's.
Do you have any research projects now that you will,
Want to work on them?
Well, I still do the pecan stuff, but all this is free.
I mean, I'm not getting paid for it.
I do it because I'm interested in it.
And the same thing with the honey.
They do pay for my hotel room, but I don't make any money off of honey or pecans.
You're getting paid in satisfaction.
Yeah, yeah, just the fun of doing it.
I do get paid for going to Guatemala to teach, but it's not money that you couldn't do without.
In your many extracurricular activities in these almost 40 years, which extracurricular activities do you most proudly remember?
You mean other than a trip to Europe?
Is that an extracurricular activity?
No, no, no.
You mean on campus?
Yeah.
Yeah, well, I think working with the MSC.
Wayne Stark was a force to be reckoned with on this campus.
How did he identify you?
Do you know?
No, I don't.
I'll bet it was through Ty Timm.
I'm guessing.
That's the way he did because he contacted me one time about somebody on our faculty.
I'm guessing through Ty, but I don't know.
And what was your role with the MSU?
I was on the council, and so was Peggy.
And so we met those kids and worked with Skona, some, as well as being on the council.
And I remember one time we took a trip to Houston with him, took the educational trip, you know, this is your fork, this is your knife, and that sort of thing.
And he did a really good, and sending kids to Harvard and places like that.
So that was a good experience for me when I first got here.
Other than that, I haven't, when President Vandenberg got here, he did an interesting thing.
He initiated the Faculty Senate, which lo and behold these many years was not welcomed on the Texas A&M campus.
I got appointed to that committee, which met about a year, and came up with a faculty senate, which I think is a good idea.
It's more of an advisory institution, but I thought that was a needed.
In this day and age, I think Texas A&M needs a faculty senate.
And I think it's pretty well behaved itself.
I think it's been beneficial.
I worked some with, what do you call these 10-year studies?
Southern Association Accreditation.
Yeah, I've been on a couple of those, and those were interesting.
It gives you some perspective on the institution, but I know there's been stuff other than that, too, but like I said, I was never a core advisor to that group.
I was on Phi Kappa Phi Honor Society for a number of years, up through the ranks, working with honor students, and that was...
A good experience for me.
And working with the graduate students, that's not extracurricular, but just seeing them come through here, a tremendous mix.
And from all over the country, they came.
Much more heterogeneous group than the undergraduates.
Of all the people that you have known here at A&M, to whom would you feel deepest gratitude?
Gratitude?
For whatever.
You mean like in a professional sense?
People that you're grateful for what they did, what they meant to you and to A&M?
Well, shoot, Haskell, I could have mentioned you.
But I'm going to bring it closer to home, I guess.
Well, as I said before, I've suffered by not seeking enough advice, I think, during my life from whoever.
But, you know, Ty hired me, so of course I'll be holding to him.
John Hopkins...
I think, was supportive.
I think John was fair.
I'm not sure I always did as much as I should for the department, but I suppose Bob Branson, Bob's been a supporter, so I credit Bob with putting up with me and being helpful.
I don't know, there's so many people it's hard to really make that, you know, answer that question and say, well, this is the guy that
because there was no really mentor as such that I went to a lot and said, tell me what to do here, tell me what to do here, although I probably should have, but I didn't.
Okay.
What were your avocations?
What did you do for fun?
For fun?
To relax.
In the early years, there used to be some guys in the department who played golf, but we always felt a little guilty about that because you weren't supposed to be off during business hours.
So I think some took leave and some didn't.
But that didn't go on many years.
I like to play handball.
We play handball at 5 o'clock, maybe twice a week with Art Gerloh.
who Art passed away a couple, three years ago.
Spell his last name.
G-E-R-L-O-W, Art Gerlo.
He was a Scandinavian Cajun from South Louisiana.
Played, you know, some tennis.
Bicycling.
Did you play handball with just him, just Art?
Well, Art, the handball players now, Stan Lowy was a handball player.
Stan Steven, who you know, was a banker.
A lot of graduate students.
We played handball with graduate students a lot over there in DeWare.
It was the better place to play.
Other applications?
Yeah, bicycling.
I did a little bit of bicycling here, there, and yonder.
We'd go to rides.
And then now it's racquetball.
with the McCandless and Buck Henderson and people of that stripe.
But other than that, camping.
We liked to camp.
That's how we used to go to meetings.
The meetings of the Agricultural Economic Association used to be held universally.
So you got to go to Washington State or Calgary, Canada,
Oklahoma State, or wherever they were, Kentucky, Montana, Wyoming.
And you took your kids and you went camping.
That's what we did.
That was a lot of fun.
A certain era in your life, you do that.
Otherwise, the church.
We teach Sunday school below these many years.
Consider that an avocation, but it's an activity that takes a lot of your time, as you know.
As
If you could give advice now to your department, what advice would you give it?
That's one of those thought questions.
I guess I would advise it to spend a lot of time trying to figure out what are the significant problems in society, economically related problems, that we should be working on.
Not that you're going to force people into niches to do their work, but I've always wondered if we spent enough time simply got research money.
We used to have more than we have now.
If we're really working on significant problems, it's bothered me that we tend to go where the money is as opposed to where the problems are.
And people with a lot of money don't always have the worst problems.
It always kind of bothered me, and I certainly wasn't going to do it, that we didn't do more work in agricultural labor, farm workers, welfare, and things like that in Texas.
But it just wasn't politically popular.
You really couldn't.
We had a guy who tried to do it, and it was not feasible to do much in that area.
So I think, as researchers, to look at the problems that are significant as far as teaching goes, that's a good question.
We're getting now into distance education and stuff like that.
Any areas of emphasis or disemphasis?
Well, I would like, I wish that our graduates, and I'm not saying that I did, but I wish they had a broader education.
I'm not saying we're vo-tech, but I'm saying we're pretty, it's a question of are we meeting the job market, as opposed to,
And we don't need to turn out liberal arts majors, but I think that we suffer from too narrow an orientation in our department.
And I wish they had, we don't even teach history of economic thought anymore.
Kids used to take, at least at the graduate level, we had a course on economics called history of economic thought.
And you went back and you looked at all the way up from Plato to Marshall and Marx and all these guys.
They don't get that now.
What they get is quantitative knowledge.
And I think we come glued to the computer.
numbers and econometric models, math, stat, that sort of thing.
I don't think that's given us a less rich life than if we had looked at where did we come from, how did we get here, what is political science, what is political economy?
And, you know, they should know who those are, who the big names in the field were, what they stood for.
Who was Keynes?
I think a lot of these kids know who Keynes was.
So I think we've missed a little bit there by not giving a little more rounded education.
So I would argue for that.
What have we not covered?
What have we not covered?
Yeah, what have we left out that you thought I was going to say?
Where do I want to be 10 years from now?
Alive.
Oh, well, we've made lots of good friends here and the collegiality of meeting people in other departments and, you know, it's amazing the contact we've had with historians and blessed by that.
And it's a great community.
We have raised our kids here.
Our kids, when we came here,
As our kids grew up, they had the run of the campus.
They could go to G Raleigh and play.
They could swim in the pool.
It was just like a little town situation, and now all that's changed.
The kids of faculty today don't have that privilege, and I'm sorry they don't, but they can't.
There's no way that would work today, but you know how it was in those days.
It was beautiful.
They rode their bikes everywhere and did what they wanted to.
As you, that caused me to ask a question I haven't asked anybody else.
As you think back, could we, could A&M have done a much better job of integrating the student body racially?
Could it have been done more skillfully, smoothly, with fewer problems?
I don't know, you know, I'm so, I guess, numb to that, that I never
really felt, I know there was problems with kids.
I had an Indian student who got harassed over here last year, two years ago, because of his race.
But I've never, I always felt the problem was more with females than it was with racial.
The racial thing was not a big deal on this campus.
It probably was, but I didn't feel it.
I really didn't.
And I don't know how the female could have been handled better
No, but it was handled, and the people, the way they reacted, you can't think about that.
It was going to happen, and I think it needed to happen.
All right, I've got three more questions here.
Of what are you most proud?
Of what am I most proud?
We're talking about professionally.
Well, I think the students that we've helped go through here, the graduate students, I've had more to do with them.
And teaching.
You never know what buttons you've touched.
But you have your moments, as you know, when lights have gone on and, in some cases, lifelong friendships from even undergraduates.
But the grad students I've worked with and we still keep in touch with, the research is important.
I think that's been helpful.
But I think there's no substitute for the people you've worked with as they came through here.
So I would say that the work
we've done with that.
The students have been the most rewarding.
Can you think of some specific moments as samples of those good times?
When this happened or somebody did this or said that?
Well, as you've seen them go out and become professors or department heads or something like that, but nothing really flashes up that strikes me.
I'm sure I could think of it if I sat here long enough.
but just in general, that they've been successful.
Getting them in here sometimes was a problem.
Let's make believe someone walks up to you and gives you a check for a million dollars with one condition.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you get to decide how they will use that money.
You can make a big gift, and you select the purpose.
What would it be for?
I don't know if it's legal, but I think I'd make it for scholarships, if you could ever figure out how, for eligible low-income kids.
Offhand, that'd be my first thought.
It would be scholarships for people who can't afford to go to school.
All right, how do you pick, then, of all those?
That's the question.
No, of all those who are low-income, how do you select the winners?
Well, they'd have to be academically qualified.
qualified, as academically qualified as anybody else, but simply can't afford to go to college.
Now, you say, well, if they're academically qualified, they're going to get a scholarship anyhow.
So maybe there's other places that are better for it, but that's my first thought, is kids who need the education but yet can't pay for it.
To major in?
I don't really care what they major in.
So they get to go to college.
Last question.
What feelings do you have in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Well, let me tell you how we were when we first got here.
Mixed for one thing, but I guess mixed on everything.
It's a unique public institution.
I can't think of another one like it.
And I remember when we first got here, we were like the average, I suppose, new, recently from the east, by way of Oklahoma.
And we thought, good God, we've come to the end of the earth.
And we weren't that sophisticated.
But it was located out here in the middle of no place.
When we got here, there was one eating place, two, I guess.
There was Arnold's Barbecue and a Rao Burger in this town.
There was no grocery store.
Well, Charlie's, but nobody shopped there.
I mean, we didn't shop there.
And we thought, ooh, where have I brought my family?
And yet it grows on you.
And then, of course, things changed.
Certainly it was, and tradition-bound and all military and all male didn't really know all that before we got here.
I don't know why they didn't register to know what made a difference or not.
But it is, A&M is a, in some cases, it's a fabulous place in terms of tradition, in terms of loyalty, in terms of devotion, and...
That sort of thing, it's beautiful.
In terms of other things, it's too, I won't use the term narrow-minded, but not open to other ideas like this gay thing, the controversy they're having and so on.
But it's a mixed bag, but we've, I guess, really come to love it.
There are times you can almost come to tears
When you go to Final Review, not Final Review, but TAPS, not TAPS, muster.
You know, you're just overcome by the whole thing.
And I did go to Silver Taps when General Rutter died.
And so there's things like that that are beautiful.
But then on the other side, you get these strange things.
The whole bonfire controversy is, it was just strange, you know, in this day and age.
It was good and bad, and you just wonder about things like that.
But anyhow, I've come to love it, and I guess I'm still an Okie, but I'm glad we came to Texas.
